{
  "doc_id": "57155",
  "text": "Others have shown that men with alcoholic fathers as well as women at high risk for developing alcoholism have higher voltage alpha power than controls [CITATION_1] . Further, Enoch et al. [CITATION_2] reported the presence of a distinctive EEG phenotype in 5 to 10% of individuals, referring to an ''alpha variant'', i.e., low-voltage alpha (LVA). This EEG trait is characterized by the virtual absence of alpha rhythmicity, and, if present, the alpha waveform is scanty and of low amplitude [CITATION_3] . The same authors reported that this variant is associated with a subtype of alcoholism that co-occurs with anxiety disorder. More recently, while studying young African-American adults, Ehlers et al. [CITATION_4] found evidence of considerable ethnic variation in the prevalence of LVA EEG variants.",
